data.value: The in depth MTG phases are as follows on the right hand side of the tab. There are 8 primary phases in a turn with 6 sub-phases in the combat phase that typically happen quickly unless needed to go slowly. At the beginning of a regular turn in MTG Untap occurs, in which no players can cast any spells or activate any abilities that creatures may have. Next phase is Upkeep, which allows for any effects on the field that say “at the beginning of your upkeep” or “at the end of your upkeep” effects to trigger. During this phase another player or yourself can declare a stop at upkeep to cast instants or activate any abilities that can be activated. The next phase is the Draw phase, where a player will draw their card for a turn. During this phase a player can also put a stop similar to upkeep, however, this stop can only be called after the card is drawn at the end of the draw step. Then begins the Main phase one, in which you can play your land per turn if you wish, cast any spells you are capable of casting from your hand, or activate any abilities of permanents (permanents are any cards on the field that stay) you control. Other players can also interact with anything you are doing at this time with a response of their own where applicable. The next phase is combat, another stop can be put at the beginning of the combat phase before the sub-phases occur. At each sub-step a stop can be called by either player to activate abilities or cast instant spells, with the only exception being the first strike/ double strike sub-phase since this phase only triggers if creatures have the ability listed as first strike and double strike. During declaring attackers the current player states which creatures they wish to attack with. During blockers the player currently being attacked by creatures can decide to block the attack with creatures of their own. Regular combat damage sub-phase is when damage is dealt to creatures and players, and cards get moved to their respective zones like creatures to the graveyard when they die. Then the end of combat occurs and each player can put another stop. Most players will simplify these steps especially when nothing needs to be done. Once combat is done Main phase two begins, which is identical to the first main phase except if you have already played a land you can no longer play one this turn. End step occurs when you declare the end of your turn, and another stop can be put here by players. The end of turn cleanup then happens when everyone is done and you discard down to standard hand size of seven cards, creatures revert to how much toughness they had before damage was dealt, and effects that specify end of turn end. Then the next player gets to go following the same steps.
